1. Reading Datasets

All the datasets were selected based on their properties, and they satisfy all the conditions given on the homework description sheet;

The dataset 2 and dataset 4 are multiclass classification problems, The dataset 3 is a regression problem, The dataset 4 has a class imbalance, The dataset 2 and the dataset 3 have more than 50 features, The dataset 4 has categorical features, All these datasets have more than 20 features, All the train and the test samples of these datasets consist of more than 200 instances.

Before the implementation of 5 different texhniques, data were converted into a sufficient format so that the procedures can be handled properly. (There were some work on missing values, factors etc.)

1.a - 1st Dataset

Data Set Characteristics:

Multivariate

Number of Instances:569, Area:Life, Attribute Characteristics:Real, Number of Attributes:32 Date Donated:1995-11-01, Associated Tasks:Classification, Missing Values:No Data Set Information:

Features are computed from a digitized image of a fine needle aspirate (FNA) of a breast mass. They describe characteristics of the cell nuclei present in the image. A few of the images can be found at [Web Link]

Separating plane described above was obtained using Multisurface Method-Tree (MSM-T) [K. P. Bennett, “Decision Tree Construction Via Linear Programming.” Proceedings of the 4th Midwest Artificial Intelligence and Cognitive Science Society, pp. 97-101, 1992], a classification method which uses linear programming to construct a decision tree. Relevant features were selected using an exhaustive search in the space of 1-4 features and 1-3 separating planes.

The actual linear program used to obtain the separating plane in the 3-dimensional space is that described in: [K. P. Bennett and O. L. Mangasarian: “Robust Linear Programming Discrimination of Two Linearly Inseparable Sets”, Optimization Methods and Software 1, 1992, 23-34].

This database is also available through the UW CS ftp server: ftp ftp.cs.wisc.edu cd math-prog/cpo-dataset/machine-learn/WDBC/

Attribute Information:

  1. ID number
  2. Diagnosis (M = malignant, B = benign) 3-32)

Ten real-valued features are computed for each cell nucleus:

  1. radius (mean of distances from center to points on the perimeter)
  2. texture (standard deviation of gray-scale values)
  3. perimeter
  4. area
  5. smoothness (local variation in radius lengths)
  6. compactness (perimeter^2 / area - 1.0)
  7. concavity (severity of concave portions of the contour)
  8. concave points (number of concave portions of the contour)
  9. symmetry
  10. fractal dimension (“coastline approximation” - 1)

This data was downloaded from: http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Breast+Cancer+Wisconsin+%28Diagnostic%29

Structure of the dataset 1 (After preprocessing)

1.b - 2nd Dataset

Data Set Characteristics:Multivariate, Number of Instances:1080, Area:Life, Attribute Characteristics:Real, Number of Attributes:82, Date Donated:2015-08-04, Associated Tasks: Classification, Clustering, Missing Values:Yes

Data Set Information:

The data set consists of the expression levels of 77 proteins/protein modifications that produced detectable signals in the nuclear fraction of cortex. There are 38 control mice and 34 trisomic mice (Down syndrome), for a total of 72 mice. In the experiments, 15 measurements were registered of each protein per sample/mouse. Therefore, for control mice, there are 38x15, or 570 measurements, and for trisomic mice, there are 34x15, or 510 measurements. The dataset contains a total of 1080 measurements per protein. Each measurement can be considered as an independent sample/mouse.

The eight classes of mice are described based on features such as genotype, behavior and treatment. According to genotype, mice can be control or trisomic. According to behavior, some mice have been stimulated to learn (context-shock) and others have not (shock-context) and in order to assess the effect of the drug memantine in recovering the ability to learn in trisomic mice, some mice have been injected with the drug and others have not.

Classes: c-CS-s: control mice, stimulated to learn, injected with saline (9 mice) c-CS-m: control mice, stimulated to learn, injected with memantine (10 mice) c-SC-s: control mice, not stimulated to learn, injected with saline (9 mice) c-SC-m: control mice, not stimulated to learn, injected with memantine (10 mice)

t-CS-s: trisomy mice, stimulated to learn, injected with saline (7 mice) t-CS-m: trisomy mice, stimulated to learn, injected with memantine (9 mice) t-SC-s: trisomy mice, not stimulated to learn, injected with saline (9 mice) t-SC-m: trisomy mice, not stimulated to learn, injected with memantine (9 mice)

The aim is to identify subsets of proteins that are discriminant between the classes.

Attribute Information:

1 Mouse ID 2..78 Values of expression levels of 77 proteins; the names of proteins are followed and indicating that they were measured in the nuclear fraction. For example: DYRK1A_n 79 Genotype: control (c) or trisomy (t) 80 Treatment type: memantine (m) or saline (s) 81 Behavior: context-shock (CS) or shock-context (SC) 82 Class: c-CS-s, c-CS-m, c-SC-s, c-SC-m, t-CS-s, t-CS-m, t-SC-s, t-SC-m

This data was downloaded from: http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Mice+Protein+Expression

Structure of the dataset 3 (After preprocessing)

1.d - 4th Dataset

Data Set Characteristics:Multivariate, Number of Instances:7195, Area:Life, Attribute Characteristics:Real, Number of Attributes:22, Date Donated: 2017-02-24, Associated Tasks: Classification, Clustering, Missing Values: N/A,

Data Set Information:

This dataset was used in several classifications tasks related to the challenge of anuran species recognition through their calls. It is a multilabel dataset with three columns of labels. This dataset was created segmenting 60 audio records belonging to 4 different families, 8 genus, and 10 species. Each audio corresponds to one specimen (an individual frog), the record ID is also included as an extra column. We used the spectral entropy and a binary cluster method to detect audio frames belonging to each syllable. The segmentation and feature extraction were carried out in Matlab. After the segmentation we got 7195 syllables, which became instances for train and test the classifier. These records were collected in situ under real noise conditions (the background sound). Some species are from the campus of Federal University of Amazonas, Manaus, others from Mata Atlantica, Brazil, and one of them from Cordoba, Argentina. The recordings were stored in wav format with 44.1kHz of sampling frequency and 32bit of resolution, which allows us to analyze signals up to 22kHz. From every extracted syllable 22 MFCCs were calculated by using 44 triangular filters. These coefficients were normalized between -1 mfcc 1. The amount of instances per class are:

Families: Bufonidae 68 Dendrobatidae 542 Hylidae 2165 Leptodactylidae 4420

Genus: Adenomera 4150 Ameerega 542 Dendropsophus 310 Hypsiboas 1593 Leptodactylus 270 Osteocephalus 114 Rhinella 68 Scinax 148

Species: AdenomeraAndre 672 AdenomeraHylaedact 3478 Ameeregatrivittata 542 HylaMinuta 310 HypsiboasCinerascens 472 HypsiboasCordoba 1121 LeptodactylusFuscus 270 OsteocephalusOoph 114 Rhinellagranulosa 68 ScinaxRuber 148

Attribute Information:

Mel-frequency cepstral coefficients (MFCCs) are coefficients that collectively make up an mel-frequency cepstrum (MFC). Due to each syllable has different length, every row (i) was normalized acording to MFCCs_i/(max(abs(MFCCs_i))).

This data was downloaded from: http://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/Anuran+Calls+%28MFCCs%29

# fit model
fit <- glmnet(new_train,as.matrix(Dataset_2_train$class) ,family="multinomial", alpha=1,
              lambda=cross_validation$lambda.min)
# summarize the fit
summary(fit)
# make predictions for train data
predictions <- predict(fit, new_train, type="class")
# summarize accuracy for train data
tab<-table(predictions[,1],Dataset_2_train$class)
print("confusion matrix for the train data")
print(tab)
train_error<-1-sum(diag(tab)/sum(tab))
print(c("train error",train_error))

# make predictions for test data
predictions <- predict(fit, new_test, type="class")
# summarize accuracy for train data
tab<-table(predictions[,1],Dataset_2_test$class)
print("confusion matrix for the test data")
print(tab)
test_error<-1-sum(diag(tab)/sum(tab))
print(c("test error",test_error))

And the following error showed up;

“Error in matrix(fit$a0[seq(lmu * nc)], nc, lmu, dimnames = list(classnames, : length of ‘dimnames’ [2] not equal to array extent In addition: Warning message: from glmnet Fortran code (error code -1); Convergence for 1th lambda value not reached after maxit=100000 iterations; solutions for larger lambdas returned”

Therefore, penalized regression approach could not be implemented on this particular data set.

3.2. - Decision Tree

In this part, the values (2,3,4) for the minimal number of observations per tree leaf and the values (0.005, 0.01, 0.015) for the complexity parameter were used respectively. All the calculations were made based on this sequence (there is a for loop for the respective values). The decision trees, train and the test errors can be seen below for the respective parameter value sequence. Also, the visual representation of the cross-validation result is given at the end of the calculations.

## Classification tree:
## rpart(formula = class ~ ., data = Dataset_2_train, control = rpart.control(minbucket = 1 +

4. Analyzes for Dataset 3

4.1. - Penalized Regression Approach

As described before, this is a regression dataset and the aim is to predict the critical temperature value (a continuous, numerical value). In this part, cross validation was implemented on the train data set and the best value of the lambda was found after 10 fold cross validation. Then this value was used on the model and this model was used for predicting the critical temperature. Since the response variable is numeric, family was selected as “Gaussian”. All the procedures, results, error rates for the performance of the model on train and the test data can be seen below. Since this is a regression problem, the performance metric is coefficient of determination.

4.3.a. - Support Vector Machines for Polynomial Kernel

In this part, the code below tried to run but it did not response since the data was too big and this is the regression analysis. It has a huge computational load.

#Support Vector Machine for Polynomial Kernel
library(e1071)
set.seed(5)
svmfit<-svm(critical_temp~.,data = Dataset_3_train,kernel="polynomial")
print(svmfit)
#Finding best cost value
tuned<-tune(svm,critical_temp~.,data = Dataset_3_train,kernel="polynomial",ranges = list(cost=c(0.001,0.01,0.1,1,10,100)))
summary(tuned)
bestcost<-as.data.frame(tuned$best.parameters)
#Using best cost value
svmfit<-svm(critical_temp~.,data = Dataset_3_train,kernel="polynomial",cost=as.numeric(bestcost[1,1]))
print(svmfit)
#Predicting test data
p<-predict(svmfit,Dataset_3_test,type="class")
plot(p)

table(p,Dataset_3_test$class)
error<-1-sum(diag(table(p,Dataset_2_test$class))/sum(table(p,Dataset_2_test$class)))
print(c("test error",error))

4. CONCLUSIONS

After the analyzes, the corresponding comments were given for all approaches. This part is a brief summary about all of these algorithms. As can be seen from the results, penalized regression approach works well on the regression problem and the classification problems with two classes. However, this approach could not give reasonable results on the classification problems with more than two classes. On the other hand, decision tree algorithm worked well on all these data sets (classification, regression, data with imbalance at least 1:3 ratio). The error rates were sufficient enough. Support vector machines also worked well on all these data sets with less error rates compared to the decision tree algorithm. More than that, some of the data sets were learned perfectly the models and the algorithm explain the response column of the data set without error. For the random forest, the algorithm works well on all the classification problems. However, for the regression dataset, the created model did not response for a long time and it has a great amount of computational load. Therefore, using random forest algorithm on the regreesion problems would not be efficient. For the stochastic gradient boosting, the algorithm again works very well on the classification cases and the corresponding error rates are quite low. However, this algorithm is not very efficient for explaining the behavior of the regression problems. The performance metric, coefficient of determination value, was not very close to 1 while the error rates of this algorithm on the classification cases were too low, which implies that this algorithm performs better on the classification problems compared to the regression problems.

# Decision Tree for dataset 1
set.seed(5)
for (i in 1:3){
  library(rpart)
  dtree1<-rpart(V2~.,data = Dataset_1_train,control = rpart.control(minbucket = 1+i,cp=0.005*i))
  a<-as.data.frame(printcp(dtree1))
  
  require(rpart.plot)
  rpart.plot(dtree1,extra = 2)
  #Predictions
  predict(dtree1,Dataset_1_test)
  #Misclassification Error for train data
  tab1t<-table(predict(dtree1,Dataset_1_train, type="class"),Dataset_1_train$V2)
  print(tab1t)
  error1t<-1-sum(diag(tab1t)/sum(tab1t))
  print(c("trainerror",error1t)) 
  #Misclassification Error for test data
  tab1tt<-table(predict(dtree1,Dataset_1_test, type="class"),Dataset_1_test$V2)
  error1tt<-1-sum(diag(tab1tt)/sum(tab1tt))
  print(c("test error",error1tt))
  error1tt
}
print("cp values for error rates")
plotcp(dtree1)

# Penalized Regression for Dataset 3
# load the package
library(glmnet)
new_train<-as.matrix(Dataset_3_train[,-82])
new_test<-as.matrix(Dataset_3_test[,-82])

cross_validation<-cv.glmnet(new_train,as.matrix(Dataset_3_train$critical_temp) ,family="gaussian", alpha=1)
plot(cross_validation)
# fit model
fit <- glmnet(new_train,as.matrix(Dataset_3_train$critical_temp),
              family="gaussian", alpha=1,lambda=cross_validation$lambda.min)
# summarize the fit
summary(fit)
# make predictions for train data
predictions <- predict(fit, new_train)
# summarize accuracy for train data
outcome<-cbind(Dataset_3_train$critical_temp, data.frame(predictions))
error=sum((outcome[,2] - mean(outcome[,2]))^2) / sum((outcome[,1] - mean(outcome[,1]))^2)
print(c("coefficient of determination (train)",error))

# make predictions for test data
predictions <- predict(fit, new_test)
# summarize accuracy for train data
outcome<-cbind(Dataset_3_test$critical_temp, data.frame(predictions))
error= sum((outcome[,1] - mean(outcome[,1]))^2) / sum((outcome[,2] - mean(outcome[,2]))^2) 
print(c("coefficient of determination (test)",error))


# Decision Tree for Dataset 3

              control = rpart.control(minbucket = 2+i,cp=0.005*i),method = "anova")
require(rpart.plot)
rpart.plot(dtree1,type = 3,digits = 3,fallen.leaves = TRUE)
#Predictions
p1<-predict(dtree1,Dataset_3_train)
#Mean Absolute Error for train data

MAE<-function(actual,predicted){mean(abs(actual - predicted))
}
p2<-predict(dtree1,Dataset_3_test)

print(c("mean absolute error for train data",MAE(Dataset_3_train$critical_temp,p1)))
print(c("mean absolute error for test data",MAE(Dataset_3_test$critical_temp,p2)))
}

plotcp(dtree1)
